  "level": "C1",
  "title": "How much of an economic boom is the 2026 FIFA World Cup for the U.S. hosting cities?",
  "description": "The FIFA World Cup is thought to bring an economic windfall to the cities and regions where games will be played during four weeks this summer. How true is that?",
  "text": "The FIFA World Cup is thought to bring an economic windfall to the cities and regions where games will be played during four weeks this summer. SCOTT DETROW, The United States, Canada and Mexico are playing host to the soccer world this month as the FIFA World Cup brings the top 48 teams in the world to North America. DYLAN DUKE, Over the course of the World Cup, thousands of fans will flow through the gates here at the FIFA Fan Fest in Dallas. DUKE: Andrew Morris flew from Australia to attend three games at the Dallas Stadium. The city of Dallas projects a 1.5 to $2 billion economic boost or about $3.5 million in sales tax revenue. DUKE: Cullum Clark is a professor of economics at Southern Methodist University in Dallas, Texas. He explained that projections from big sports events like the World Cup are generally exaggerated. Clark said Dallas already has airports, highways, public transportation and entertainment districts to support the World Cup. CLARK: When the games come to town, it's sort of like a validation, like yes - yes, you are a serious city that did make yourself an obvious host. People like Andrew Morris are flying into Dallas and the other host cities to spend money on hotels, food and their favorite team's jersey.",
